    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral, third-party vault where funds and documents are held safely until the deal is officially closed, ensuring neither the buyer nor the seller can tamper with the process. In Toronto, this is crucial because the real estate market is so competitive and complex that a single misstep could leave you holding a deposit that disappears into the void, or worse, a seller who walks away with your money.\n\nThink of it like a very serious, very organized group of three-legged goblins who are sworn to secrecy and absolute neutrality. These goblins don't care about you or the seller; they only care about the contract. They sit in the middle, holding the keys to the house and the cash in their little pouches, waiting for the final \"hush\" signal from the lawyer to release everything. Without them, you'd be trusting a stranger with your life savings and the deed to your future home, which is a recipe for disaster.\n\nIn your specific case, the escrow agent acts as the gatekeeper. They ensure the mortgage approval is in place, the inspection reports are clear, and the title search shows no hidden liens before the final transfer. It's the same as a construction site where the fore",
      "source": "target",
