    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The mechanism that keeps funds locked away is a combination of strict legal authority and banking protocols. The escrow agent (often a lawyer in Ontario) holds the title to the funds in a specific, segregated bank account that is legally distinct from their personal or business accounts. They cannot access these funds until the specific conditions in the purchase agreement are met, such as the buyer's mortgage approval or the completion of inspections.\n\nOnce the deal closes, the agent receives a \"closing statement\" signed by both parties and the lender, which acts as the official instruction to release the money. This document is filed with the Land Titles Office, creating a public record that the transfer is authorized. Without this signed instruction, the bank will not process the withdrawal, effectively making the funds inaccessible to anyone other than the designated recipients.\n\nIn Toronto, this process is further secured by the Land Titles Act, which requires the registration of the new ownership details before the transaction is considered complete. This ensures that even if someone tried to bypass the agent, the legal system would not recognize the transfer until the proper paperwork and funds were in place.",
